# Intuition
Since our operations of moving ahead or moving down a directory depend on the current string we see, so data structure that comes to mind is Stack

If you have used linux based system you must be already aware of these
- /abc/  --> means get into the folder /abc/
- /./  --> "." indicates current directory, that is stay where you are
- /../ --> ".." means step down a directory where you are, equivalent to a back in windows.

- Now Lets understand by an **Example**
**Input**: "/a/./b/../../c/"
**Output**: /c
We always start with home directory
After spilting Array ["a", ".", "b", "..", "..", "c]
"a" --> move to /a
"." --> stay in current directory still in /a
"b" --> move to directory b i.e /a/b
".." --> move back i.e is /a again
".." --> move back i.e back to home directory /
"c" --> move to c directory i.e /c
Answer is /c
---

# Approach
1) Split the input string on basis of '/'
This will separate all input will also resolve are double '//' cases(leading to "" empty string).
2) Now that we got a '/' speparated string array
3) We define a skip set ("..", ".", "")
- if we encouter "." means stay in the current directory
- "" is a result of // being separated, so skip that
I mainted a skip set to write clean code

```
if(!dir.equals("..") || !dir.equals(".") || !dir.equals(""))
//instead did this
if(!skip.contains(dir))
```
4) Now we start iterating over array. 
- If we encouter ".." and stack is non empty than we need to pop-out or move backwards
- If we encounter anything other than these ("..", ".", "") we add to stack
5) At end, form a Stringbuilder out of the stack.
### Why StringBuilder and not String is being used. [See this](https://leetcode.com/problems/removing-stars-from-a-string/solutions/3402865/java-explained-why-use-stringbuilder-than-string-beginner-friendly/)

---


# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(n) : Since we are going through all the elements of the string once.

---

Hope it is easy to understand.
Let me know if there is something unclear and i can fix it.

Otherwise, please upvote if you like the solution, it would be encouraging

