**Handling overflow in c/cpp**
The question does not speak about overflow or the size of the string input. So it is clear that the answer can fit in int.

But it is possible that overflow could occur in one of the intermediate steps, if you are not careful.

The below code is an example:


	int toNum(char a) {
        return a - 'A' + 1;
    }

    int titleToNumber(string s) {
        int n = s.size();
        int factor = 1, ans = 0;

        for(int i=n-1;i>=0;i--) {
            int num = toNum(s[i]);
            ans += num * factor;
            factor *= 26; // ----- overflow can occur here
        }

        return ans;
    }
You can observe that factor is multiplied by 26 at the end of the loop, hence it is ahead of the current iteration. The new value of factor that is calculated at an iteration is used only in the next iteration. Which will lead to an unnecessary calculation of factor at the last iteration of the loop. 

Let us try debugging:

	for(int i=n-1;i>=0;i--) {
		cout<<"loop begin : i="<<i<<" char:"<<s[i]<<" factor:"<<factor<<" ans:"<<ans<<endl;
		int num = toNum(s[i]);
		ans += num * factor;
		factor *= 26;
		cout<<"loop end    : i="<<i<<" char:"<<s[i]<<" factor:"<<factor<<" ans:"<<ans<<endl;
		cout<<endl;
	}

	Output:

	loop begin : i=6 char:M factor:1 ans:0
	loop end   : i=6 char:M factor:26 ans:13

	loop begin : i=5 char:X factor:26 ans:13
	loop end   : i=5 char:X factor:676 ans:637

	loop begin : i=4 char:S factor:676 ans:637
	loop end   : i=4 char:S factor:17576 ans:13481

	loop begin : i=3 char:G factor:17576 ans:13481
	loop end   : i=3 char:G factor:456976 ans:136513

	loop begin : i=2 char:D factor:456976 ans:136513
	loop end   : i=2 char:D factor:11881376 ans:1964417

	loop begin : i=1 char:F factor:11881376 ans:1964417
	loop end   : i=1 char:F factor:308915776 ans:73252673

	loop begin : i=0 char:C factor:308915776 ans:73252673

	runtime error: signed integer overflow: 308915776 * 26 cannot be represented in type 'int' (solution.cpp)


This can be solved by avoiding the factor calculation at the last iteration.

```
for(int i=n-1;i>=0;i--) {
	int num = toNum(s[i]);
	ans += num * factor;
	if(i!=0)
	factor *= 26;
}
```
But the fix looks hacky.
It is always good to learn and write cleaner code like this:

```
int toNum(char a) {
	return a - 'A' + 1;
}

int titleToNumber(string s) {
	int n = s.size();
	int ans = 0;

	for(int i=0;i<n;i++) {
		ans = ans*26 + toNum(s[i]);
	}

	return ans;
}
```
We do not do any unnecessary calculations in the above solution.

