010 (a) +
__
001 <- This line is a ^ b (XOR)
100 <- this line is the shifted version of the carry by 1 place left (a & b) << 1
__
101 <-- Our answer

So we can conclude that the sum `c` given two integers `a` and `b` will be `a ^ b` until our carry is zero. If the carry is not zero, we reassign it to integer `b`. Negatives don't need a special case, thats the beauty of this solution. If it took you a while to get this solution, don't worry, but once you understand it, its makes so much sense.

### Solution Recursion
```
    public int getSum(int a, int b) {
        if (a == 0) return b;
        if (b == 0) return a;
        return getSum(a ^ b, (a & b) << 1);
    }
```

### Solution Iterative
```
    public int getSum(int a, int b) {
        if (a == 0) return b;
        if (b == 0) return a;

        while (b != 0)  {
            int carry = (a & b) << 1;
            a = a ^ b;
            b = carry; // reassign the carry into b
        }
        return a;
    }
```

