Here's the matrix for all the possibilities of answers. 

```plain
       1  2  3  4 presses
1      2, 2, 2, 2
2      3, 4, 4, 4
3      4, 7, 8, 8
4      4, 7, 8, 8
lights

* 0 press = 1
* for presses more than 4, if presses % 2 == 1 check 3 presses, otherwise 4 presses
```

There are countless ways to hard-code this matrix, but it is more important to know where these numbers come from.

First is the brute-force solution. It takes about 1 second. The code uses a string to represent the lights and then switches the light with 4 buttons. Using a set to remove duplicated patterns.

```java
int flipLights(int n, int presses) {
    Set<String> set = new HashSet<>();
    StringBuilder builder = new StringBuilder();
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        builder.append('1');
    }
    set.add(builder.toString());
    for (int t = 0; t < presses; t++) {
        Set<String> newSet = new HashSet<>();
        for (String s : set) {
            // button 1
            char[] cs = s.toCharArray();
            for (int i = 0; i < length; i++) {
                cs[i] = (cs[i] == '1' ? '0' : '1');
            }
            newSet.add(new String(cs));

            // button 2
            cs = s.toCharArray();
            for (int i = 0; i < length; i += 2) {
                cs[i] = (cs[i] == '1' ? '0' : '1');
            }
            newSet.add(new String(cs));

            // button 3
            cs = s.toCharArray();
            for (int i = 1; i < length; i += 2) {
                cs[i] = (cs[i] == '1' ? '0' : '1');
            }
            newSet.add(new String(cs));

            // button 4
            cs = s.toCharArray();
            for (int i = 0; i < length; i += 3) {
                cs[i] = (cs[i] == '1' ? '0' : '1');
            }
            newSet.add(new String(cs));
        }
        set = newSet;
    }
    return set.size();
}
```

A quick optimization to reduce the time is to check how many lights we need to care about. There are 4 buttons, each button flips different lights. 

```plain
light 1 button 1, 3, 4
light 2 button 1, 2
light 3 button 1, 3
light 4 button 1, 2, 4
light 5 button 1, 3
light 6 button 1, 2
light 7 button 1, 3, 4
...
```

What we can see here is the first 4 lights have all the combinations of buttons. We can use these 4 lights as the sample to check all the patterns. 

```java
int flipLights(int n, int times) {
    n = Math.min(n, 4);
	// ...
}
```

This optimization gives me a solution with 55ms. It could be better, because 4 lights can be represented with a byte with 8 bits and you can flip the bit with xor bitwise operation.

On the other hand, there should be some way to reduce the presses as well. 

If we think of the status of each light, **its final status depends on the count of operations to the light**. For example, 3 times means off, 4 times means on. If the count is an odd, the light is off, otherwise on.

This theory gives me an idea that **the order of the operations doesn't matter** here since you only need to count the operations.

Another observation is **if the same button is pressed twice, the result doesn't change**. Adding an even number to an odd number is still an odd number.

With these two observations, when considering the final status, the count of pressing each button could be simplified to

* button 1: 0 times or once
* button 2: 0 times or once
* button 3: 0 times or once
* button 4: 0 times or once

any even number becomes 0, any odd number becomes 1 here. In other words, **presses more than 4 can always be reduced to 4 or less**. 

This is a big step but we need to think carefully about the button combinations here.

```plain
presses
1: 
unique buttons: {1}, {2}, {3}, {4}

2: 
press button x twice: {}
unique buttons: {1, 2}, {1, 3}, {1, 4}, {2, 3}, {2, 4}, {3, 4}

3: 
press button x twice: {1}, {2}, {3}, {4}
unique buttons: {1, 2, 3}, {1, 2, 4}, {1, 3, 4}, {2, 3, 4}

4: 
press button x 4 times: {}
press button x twice: {1, 2}, {1, 3}, {1, 4}, {2, 3}, {2, 4}, {3, 4}
unique buttons: {1, 2, 3, 4}

5: same as 3
6: same as 4
7: same as 3
...
```

Some people would continue to find the patterns to reduce the combinations, I think it is good enough since we have only 4 cases here.

The code to calculate the patterns. This time I also add bit manipulation to do the flipping.

```java
public int flipLights(int n, int presses) {
    if (presses == 0) return 1;

    int maxPresses = presses;
    if (presses > 4) {
        maxPresses = (presses % 2 == 1 ? 3 : 4);
    }
    return countPatterns(Math.min(n, 4), maxPresses);
}

int countPatterns(int lights, int maxPresses) {
    if (maxPresses == 1) {
        return countPatterns(lights, Arrays.asList(Collections.singletonList(1), Collections.singletonList(2),
                Collections.singletonList(3), Collections.singletonList(4)));
    }
    if (maxPresses == 2) {
        return countPatterns(lights, Arrays.asList(Collections.emptyList(), Arrays.asList(1, 2), Arrays.asList(1, 3),
                Arrays.asList(1, 4), Arrays.asList(2, 3), Arrays.asList(2, 4), Arrays.asList(3, 4)));
    }
    if (maxPresses == 3) {
        return countPatterns(lights, Arrays.asList(Collections.singletonList(1), Collections.singletonList(2),
                Collections.singletonList(3), Collections.singletonList(4),
                Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3), Arrays.asList(1, 2, 4), Arrays.asList(1, 3, 4), Arrays.asList(2, 3, 4)));
    }
    // 4
    return countPatterns(lights, Arrays.asList(Collections.emptyList(), Arrays.asList(1, 2), Arrays.asList(1, 3),
            Arrays.asList(1, 4), Arrays.asList(2, 3), Arrays.asList(2, 4), Arrays.asList(3, 4), Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4)));
}

int countPatterns(int lights, List<List<Integer>> combinations) {
    int base = (1 << lights) - 1;
    Set<Integer> patterns = new HashSet<>();
    for (List<Integer> instructions : combinations) {
        patterns.addAll(pressButtons(base, instructions));
    }
    return patterns.size();
}

private Set<Integer> pressButtons(int base, List<Integer> instructions) {
    Set<Integer> prev = new HashSet<>();
    prev.add(base);
    for (Integer button : instructions) {
        Set<Integer> next = new HashSet<>();
        for (Integer n : prev) {
            if (button == 1) {
			    // if we have only 3 lights, we need 0b111 here so using base as the mask
                next.add(n ^ (base & 0b1111));
            } else if (button == 2) {
                next.add(n ^ (base & 0b0101));
            } else if (button == 3) {
                next.add(n ^ (base & 0b1010));
            } else { // 4
                next.add(n ^ (base & 0b1001));
            }
        }
        prev = next;
    }
    return prev;
}
```

This solution only takes 5ms. In principal we don't need to do optimization any more. If you want to use some hard-coded answers, do a simple 4x4 loop to generate the matrix at the first of this post.

Hope this post helps.

