```
/*x:the times use button1, y:the times use button2 z: the times use button3 w: the times use button4
the order do not infulence the ans ;and the first 4 light will decide the ans; 

for the light1 is always the same as light7 , light2 is always the same as light8... under different operations,
so we concentrate on the first 6 light ,but light2 is always the same as light6, light3 is always the same as 5,
so we only concentrate on the first 4 light;

we can list the equations:
x+y+z+w=m  
x+z+w=k1(mod2) (k1%2 decide the ans on light1)
x+y = k2(mod2) (k2%2 the ans on light2)
x+z=k3(mod2)  (k3%2 decide the ans on light3) 
x+y+w=k4(mod2) (k4%2 decide the ans on light4) 
so we can fix x,y,z(mod2), to get w(mod2) , and statistics the different ans of tuple [k1,k2,k3] !
*/
class Solution {
public:
    int flipLights(int n, int m) {
        n=(n>4)?4:n;
        std::set<int> set;
        for(int i = 0;i<8;++i)
        {
            int x=i&1;
            int y=(i>>1)&1;
            int z = (i>>2)&1;
            int w=m-x-y-z;
            if(w>=0)
            {
                w=w%2;
                int b[4]={(x+z+w)%2,(x+y)%2,(x+z)%2,(x+y+w)%2};
                int k=0;
                for(int t=0;t<n;++t)
                {
                    k+=(b[t]<<t);
                }
                set.insert(k);
            }
        }
        return set.size();
    }
};
```

